Broad-range PTM searches with Sipros on Titan .All Raw ﬁles were converted to FT1 and FT2 ﬂat ﬁles using Raxport (http://raxport.omicsbio.org) and searched using Sipros (http://sipros.omicsbio.org).

A trypsin-digested GS2 AMD sample was ﬁrst searched against the complete AMD database containing 79,633 proteins (available at the Chorus Project website,https://chorusproject.org/anonymous/download/experiment/2640012360637 03668), which were derived from B80 billion base pairs of genomic information obtained from previous metagenomic characterizations of the Richmond MineAMD system (NCBI BioProject accession code PRJNA20823).

The ﬁnal AMD database for PTM searches contained 15,523 proteins from seven organisms (available at the Chorus Project website, https://chorusproject.org/anonymous/download/experiment/-7500136186166692913), including Leptospir- illum group II UBA, Leptospirillum group II 5wayCG, Leptospirillum group III, and four archaea 50(Ferroplasma I, G plasma, E plasma and A plasma).The broad-range PTM searches were conducted with Sipros 3.0 on a supercomputer, Titan, at Oak Ridge Leadership Computing Facility.
Relative quantiﬁcation of protein abundance.All quantiﬁcation was conducted with ProRata53(http://prorata.omicsbio.org).
Sequence alignment was performed using EMBOSS Needle55(http://www.ebi.ac.uk/Tools/ psa/emboss_needle/).
PyMOL(http://www.pymol.org) was then used to display the protein structures and mark the modiﬁed sites by ball structures.
